column1: Data Supplied By: National Livestock Reporting Service
Data source: National Livestock Reporting Service
Please see terms of use here: https://www.mla.com.au/general/Terms-and-conditions/data-and-information/

There were approximately 740 export and 50 young cattle penned representing an increase of 250 head from the sale of a fortnight ago. Most of the usual buying group was present and operating in a cheaper market. Quality was lacking in the prime section while cows represented 2 thirds of the sale. The limited selection of young cattle eased around 20c/kg for most. Grown cattle lost 20c to 30c/kg. Cows eased 25c/kg on most sales. Heavy bulls slipped 30c/kg. 

A handful of vealers lacking finish reached 240c/kg. A few yearling steers suited to the trade sold from 270c to 296c with plainer lots suited to restockers from 188c to 280c/kg. Yearling heifers to the trade made between 230c and 296c/kg. Grown steers and bullocks sold between 230c and 292c/kg. 

Heavy Friesian manufacturing steers made from 178c to 212c with the crossbred portion from 190c to 272c/kg. Most light and medium weight cows sold from 83c to 210c/kg. Heavy weight cows made mostly between 151c and 243c/kg. Heavy bulls sold between 202c and 227c/kg. 

Market reporter: Brendan Fletcher.
